tip.text: Signature briyani is a flavor packed dish, but siewyok should have crackling skin and this did not, which was disappointing. Decent dishes but certainly overhyped.

contact.facebookName: Meat The Porkers - Porky Indian Cuisine

tip.text: The place to be for fallafels! Line may be long, but staff are super efficient. (7/10)
Cozy place, great staff, delicious crepes! Make it a point to swing by if you're a tourist! (8/10)
Pizzas are great, impressive selection. Buy slices by the combos to get the best value for money! (8/10)
Crazy line in and always sold out. Prices are excluding VAT, so as a tourist, I was not anticipating the extra $$$.
Service could be better, and our tomahawk could have been cooked better. Medium rare came out a little more done than we expected, and sides were fairly normal, given high prices. (6/10)

formattedAddress: Traders Hotel, Kuala Lumpur (Kuala Lumpur City Centre)

tip.text: It was 3 years since I was at Wild Honey and I'm disappointed to report that the English breakfast is no longer as good as it used to be. Still top service, but wish the food would still wow us (6/10)
Nice cozy place, with great ramen. Broth is thick, but tasty. Noodles pleasant and springy. Would certainly recommend 8/10.
Atrocious service despite being at 50% capacity. Also, they served a charred medium patty (which tasted bitter in parts) and despite us sending it back to the kitchen, was told that this is normal.
Excellent homey inn, with fantastic food served below. Bottle of vodka in room helps to make the stay much better!
Best fish&chips in town, for sure. Don't go for the large fish unless you can stomach it! Wash it down with a nice, cold cider.
Fantastic steak, cooked right with creamed spinach. Very decently priced, and ice cream delight after. Yassss...
Scones and cream? Forget Ms Marples, Kallista is THE place to be, for the best scones around! Remember to also try the hot chocolate!
Honestly, we tried a few pies, and none that were great. Tourist trap. Not worth the line.
Beautiful little town on the Great Ocean Road. Definitely worth a stop; spend a night or two to relax and unwind. Someday, I will be back here.
Excellent ambiance and really good coffee. I could only afford one trip here, and wish I had planned for at least two visits!
Massive line, lots of hype, super long wait to get in... but did not impress this southeast Asian.
Very interesting food, reasonable prices, excellent service. Definitely worth a try for all the foodies out there.
Japas fun dining- so small tapas like portions, but essentially Japanese food. Some were more technical, but tasted only okay. Wish my mind was blown more. Excellent service, expensive prices.
For all the hoohah I've heard about this place, hakka noodles were only so-so. Charsiew was decent, but not the best I've had.
Massive hype about this place, so thought I'd check it out. Was lucky not to have to wait too long, but the food was... only okay. Prices are very reasonable, but food left me disappointed. Pass.
This stall belongs to Ah Leng senior. Pretty good ckt as well, although slightly on the wet side. Go for the one with extra prawns. Yum!

venue.name: Ah Leng Char Koay Teow & Fried Rice 亞龍炒粿條

tip.text: Since the first time I was here, service has gone down and food takes forever to be served. I'd have recommended this place to others before, but now I can't. Average 45mins serving time; even brunch.
Good, very balanced meal. Not bad, but I was looking more to be wow-ed. Still, worthy gastronomic meal.
Good service, decent food, presented in an interesting way. Seafood is fresh, which is a big plus. Certainly worth a try. We had a platter for 4 with 2 sides and 4 drinks, bill came up to some RM320.

formattedAddress: A-1F-3, Garden Office @ Encorp Strand (No.12, Jalan PJU 5/1)

tip.text: Good, not great, food here. Staff are friendly, but should have let us know when we were ordering way too much for two persons. Black pepper bread is phenomenal!
I heard good things about the ribs, but was left disappointed. Cooked very well, but with little flavor. Sauce helped to save the day, but still not happy with my flat ribs.

formattedAddress: 2, Jalan 20/70A, Desa Sri Hartamas (Jalan Sri Hartamas 22)

tip.text: How things have changed over time. Eggs and mushrooms were bland. Beef sausage over salted. Hashbrown... it's like mashbrown. Won't be coming back.
Excellent Wagyu, nicely rendered and cooked too perfection. Curiously, the sides feel like they were microwaved. Also make sure to try the Minestrone soup, especially on a cold, rainy day.
Great service, good ambiance, decent food, but shocking prices. Nice place for a date, and certainly worth a try.

location.address: Ground Floor, The Somerset, 8 Lorong Ceylon, 50250
formattedAddress: Ground Floor, The Somerset, 8 Lorong Ceylon, 50250

tip.text: The all-new Yut Kee maintains most of its former charm, and still serves great food. Leave your name at the counter, and wait your turn to be seated. Nothing much else has changed... perfect 👍

contact.facebookName: 镒记茶餐室 Yut Kee (1928), Jalan Dang Wangi

tip.text: Space is limited, so call to make a reservation - best seats by the bar. Both chefs are friendly, so chat them up. Omakase is cheaper over lunch, but you're looking to spend about RM400/pax.

formattedAddress: A-0-1, Ground Floor St. Mary Residence (No.1 Jalan Tengah)
location.address: A-0-1, Ground Floor St. Mary Residence

tip.text: Dessert joint that stays open till late at night. Whatever you try, just don't go for the taufoo fah icecream. Mango, choc chips, and taufoo fah just don't go together... 5/10
Like all good food in HK, there is always a queue. Kau Kee doesn't disappoint; tender chunks of braised beef, although you need to pick the right noodles. Curry beef also worth a try! 7/10
Huge portions, but the food was not impressive in the least. I wouldn't recommend the goose; stick to the more popular roast goose joints. 3/10
Pierre Hermé undoubtedly has some of the best Macarons around; better than even Laduree. They're expensive, but worth every mouth sized bite. Be sure to try the dark chocolate! Yum! 9/10
One of the older, localized steakhouses in HK, it's black pepper sizzling steak is mouthwatering and absolutely fantastic! Wish I had the time to come here to try more food! 8/10

venue.name: Sweetheart Garden Restaurant 花園餐廳

tip.text: This Tim Ho Wan outlet is TKO is much less crowded, and although dimsum is only so-so, the baked charsiew pau is really all that and a definite must-try! 6/10 (8/10 for that baked charsiew pau!)

venue.name: Tim Ho Wan 添好運點心專門店

tip.text: Some fusion food don't sound right- like this egg-custard filled croissant. But holy crap, it works! A must-try! 8/10

location.address: Shop 322, Landmark, 12-16 Des Voeux Rd C
formattedAddress: Shop 322, Landmark, 12-16 Des Voeux Rd C

tip.text: All things here are pricey, and whilst the bird eye view is good, doesn't look towards sunrise or sunset. Still, definitely worth coming as the drinks are good and staff friendly. And free flow nuts!

location.address: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W
formattedAddress: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W

tip.text: Sounds simple, but ADC makes fantastic scrambled eggs, on good 'ol simple toast. Must try for tourists, although try a weekday instead of a weekend to avoid a crazy crowd!

venue.name: Australia Dairy Company (澳洲牛奶公司)

tip.text: Udon is even all-around, with a chewy texture which makes it fantastic! Broth is slightly over seasoned, but tempura is unfortunately way over. Definitely worth a try, but stick with the udon. 6.5/10

location.address: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W
formattedAddress: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W

location.address: Shop 211, 2/F, The Landmark, 15 Queen's Rd C
formattedAddress: Shop 211, 2/F, The Landmark, 15 Queen's Rd C

tip.text: Tried the fried chicken and beef ribs; but was somewhat disappointed. Food was under seasoned and tasted almost bland and prices aren't cheap (Rm75 for 2 pax)! Tht said, portions are above average.

formattedAddress: 60000 Taman Tun Dr Ismail, Kuala Lumpur

tip.text: Try the braised beef ribs, very tender. Again, the fusion might not suit everyone palate. But worth a try. Fantastic service, and decent prices though portions are on the small side.
Good food, served in a crepé. Lots to sample, but you never go wrong with anything mushroom! Great place for a lazy brunch but space is limited so go early to avoid the crowd. A bit pricey.
Old school coffee shop supposedly famed for their roast meats. I tried duck and charsiew rice - charsiew 7/10, duck 6.5/10. Sauce was lackluster. Will be back to sample the wanton noodles.

venue.name: Restaurant Hung Kee 亨记茶餐室

tip.text: Finally tried the char kuey teow here, and it was good. Really good. A bit on the oily side, but likely the best dish here. Decently priced at RM5/plate, this is a must-try!
You know what they say; once you've tried prawn mee in Penang, nothing else compares. This seemed to lack some flavour in the broth, although portions were generous (prawns tiny) and prices, decent.
Came here on a cold, rainy night and genuinely enjoyed our hot pot. Service was a little below average; staff were inattentive. Will come back to sample more food.
Quaint little cafe in Sentul area. Good ambiance, decent coffee (roasted just behind the counter area), limited choice of food, above average prices, but overall good experience.

formattedAddress: D7 (Lot G-18), Jalan Sentul, Sentul East
location.address: D7 (Lot G-18), Jalan Sentul, Sentul East

tip.text: For under RM10, you're not going to find better ramen than here. Broth isn't top-notch, but you can't compare with Ippudo! Generous portions of ramen & seaweed. Also try the gyoza; I liked them.
Great ambiance, but limited choices of (pricey) food. Must try the Carprese Ciabatta; very tasty treat. Good selection of cakes. Coffee is only ok. Will come back to sample more.

location.address: Lot G110 Ground Floor, Bangsar Shopping Centre
formattedAddress: Lot G110 Ground Floor, Bangsar Shopping Centre

tip.text: Ridiculously large sized coffees mean they taste as bad as they look. Wasn't sure if I was served a root beer or grande latté! Poached eggs over-done. Everything over priced. Not coming back.

location.address: Soho KL (Lot J-G-09), Solaris Mont Kiara, No. 2, Jalan Solaris
formattedAddress: Soho KL (Lot J-G-09), Solaris Mont Kiara, No. 2, Jalan Solaris

tip.text: A different experience altogether that is worth trying out, to explore the rest of your sense. Food was only decent, but service was excellent. Menu rotates every month, so will definitely try again.

contact.facebookName: Dining in the dark - Kuala Lumpur

tip.text: An Izakaya in the Tmn Bukit Desa neighbourhood that serves authentic udon. Some of the best I've had yet. Try the Wakame Udon that is served with chunks of seaweed for just Rm6!
Chicken rice, served with a quirky asam laksa broth. Unconventional, but the asam laksa was fantastic and completely outshone the chicken. Worth a try, but not mind blowing awesome.

venue.name: Beng Huat Asam Fish Chicken Rice

tip.text: Came here because of good reviews, but left disappointed. Nothing really special, and pretty normal dishes too. Not bad, but not mind blowing.

venue.name: 113 Fried Porridge Restaurant (113 Fried Porridge And Catering)

tip.text: Great tasting laksa, and for only Rm3.50/bowl! Try the Siam Laksa for a curry-tasting laksa, without the santan. For those looking for something different, this is a must-try!

venue.name: Kafe Khoon Hiang (亚龙炒粿条 Ah Leng Char Koay Teow) (Kafe Khoon Hiang)
Kafe Khoon Hiang (亚龙炒粿条 Ah Leng Char Koay Teow) (Kafe Khoon Hiang)
